content: Welcome to the tutorial presentation
Here is the general outline of what you will learn
How to use the editor itself.
What elements can be added to your presentations.
How to export and import your presentations.
How to add images.
How to add addition information to your elements (metadata).
How to restrict how much content can be on a given slide.
What are lanes and how to utilize them.
How to add custom styling to your presentations.
How to traverse the presentation in a non linear fashion.
proceed to the next slide to begin!
The Editor
The main part of the editor you will be interacting with is the
editor window
. You can edit one selected slide in the editor. The editor can be either on the left or right side of the screen, or stretched to fullscreen.
You can see live feedback of your slide with the
preview
feature. You can switch between the two of them with the
view
select box.
Editor - Top Menu
On the top you can find several buttons that mainly serve purpose outside of the presentation itself. We will go into most of them in more detail later, but a short summary can be found here.
File
The file dropdown menu is used for creating new presentations, exporting your current presentation and importing your already existing presentations as well as adding styles.
View
Here you can switch between a single editor/preview and a split screen.
Lanes
Everything that has to do with lanes can be found here.
Metadata
Metadata that need to be added to multiple places in the presentation can be edited here.
Constraints
For adding restrictions on your slides, so they don't feel overcrowded.
Images
Here you can add images that can be referenced in your presentation.
Editor - Editor menu
The editor menu can be found between the editor and the top menu. You likely had to interact with it already to read this slide.
The first row contains the selected lane and whether you are editing it or previewing it.

The second row contains slides themselves. Starting from the right you can delete the selected slide, add a new one and (de)activate the currect slide. You can also view infromation about your slide. Here a warning will be displayed when you reach any of the custom set constraints.
Lastly slides can be selected on the left as well as reordered by dragging them.
Contents of the presenation
As you've probably noticed, the presentation itself is written in markdown. Most of the basic features of markdown are supported such as:
paragraphs with
bold
and
italic
text
headings
of up to 6 sizes
lists
and numbered lists
blockquotes
code sections
images
img:kitten.png
and links
https://github.com/OlcorOlcor/OpenPresentationsForEducation
Importing and exporting your presentation
You can export your presentation in various ways.
All of them can be found in the File menu.
First we have the Save option. This will export the presentation in JSON. You can either save it locally or to a URL of your choosing.
Secondly we have exporting to HTML.
Currently there are two options supported.
First is the Reveal option which will export two lanes of your choosing in a Reveal.js presentation.
The second is the plain HTML option, this allows you to add a custom JavaScript script that gets appended to the exported file.
This way you can modify the presentation to your hearts desire.
Images
We already saw how to put an image on a slide. However how do you display an image from your file system?
You need to open the dialog window with the
images
button in the top menu.
There you can add an image from your file system and name it for referencing in our presentation.
When referencing an uploaded image, the prefix
img:
has to be used.
During export the images are bundled together with the rest of the presentation. So you don't need to worry about keeping them in the same directory.
Metadata
Not everything needs to be displayed on the slide. Sometimes we just want to add additional information for the curious listener or guiding information for styling.
We can add metadata in two different ways.
Global metadata
Accessed in the Metadata dialog in the top menu
Used for adding multiple information to several elements
Local metadata
Used for one off additional information
In either case they are assigned using markdown comments.
This paragraph has the global_example tag. You can check its contents in the metadata dialog.
This heading has the local metadata tag with value "cat" assigned to it
Metadata - sections
In addition to global and local metadata, we can define sections.
Sections assing a tag to multiple elements. This is especially useful when paired with CSS styling for giving the slide a layout.
Sections are like local metadata, but start with + symbol.

Front matter
A specific case of metadata are metadata for the slide itself.
This is achieved with a so called front matter.
You can see the syntax up top, any information can be added for later reference.
Lanes
Lanes are collections of slides. You can think of them as one linear part of the presentation. Lanes can be added and modified in the Lanes button in the top menu.
You can switch your active lane in the lane menu.
Lanes can be used as optional chapters of our presentation or even as speaker notes.
Styling
We give full control of styling of the presentation to you!
Acessed through File > Import Style you can add your own css style sheet. Pair this with metadata tags and turn your presentation into a work of art.
More specifically metadata add the
data-tag=""
attribute to the specific element. This can be selected using CSS.
Constraints
Sometimes we want to keep our presentations brief and clutter free. For this we can define constraints.
We can definte constraints in the constraints dialog accessed from the top menu.
This tutorial presentation has a constraint for headings set to 3. This slide reached that limit.
You can check what your slide contains with the information button in editor menu.
